<div id="review_468874536" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/468874536" />
    <a title="Dozo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15133271-dozo"><img alt="Dozo" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/468874536?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dozo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dozo" href="/user/show/15133271-dozo">Dozo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780330507769" href="/book/show/9141015-the-fear">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer468874536" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16739773403843098024">Peter Godwin returns to Zimbabwe to see the destruction spread by the increasingly teetering Mugabe regime. Having lost national elections, Mugabe turns his rage towards opposition supporters as well as his increasingly deprived people. Godwin meets and interviews key people in Zimbabwe&apos;s opposition and victims of Mugabe&apos;s sympathisers, chronicling their fate at the hands of &quot;The Fear&quot;. While the book is depressing and harrowing, it becomes apparent that unlike in his previous books, Godwin no l</span>
  <span id="freeText16739773403843098024" style="display:none">Peter Godwin returns to Zimbabwe to see the destruction spread by the increasingly teetering Mugabe regime. Having lost national elections, Mugabe turns his rage towards opposition supporters as well as his increasingly deprived people. Godwin meets and interviews key people in Zimbabwe's opposition and victims of Mugabe's sympathisers, chronicling their fate at the hands of "The Fear". While the book is depressing and harrowing, it becomes apparent that unlike in his previous books, Godwin no longer has any current link with Zimbabwe. He is playing the role of international journalist reporting shocking horrors rather than sharing his personal experience. This sense of barrier between Godwin and the general Zimbabwe populous means that even with the completely shocking scenes described, the book is not as touching as Mukiwa and Crocodile. It's hard to know what Godwin wants us to think - does he want us to run to help or just understand what is happening? Maybe a bit of both, yet from his comfortable life abroad and with a funded book contract and a house provided for writing (revealed in the credits), Godwin is unable to tell us anything that any other journalist hasn't already about Mugabe's evil regime.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16739773403843098024" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


